\frame{
\frametitle{Health economic outcome}
\begin{itemize}
\item One of the most important characteristic of health economic data is that we have \textbf{\myblue multivariate outcomes}
\begin{itemize}
\item $\myblue e$ = suitable measure of clinical benefit of an intervention
\item $\myblue c$ = suitable costs associated with an intervention 
\end{itemize}
\vspace{5pt}\pause
\item We typically need to assess these quantities \textbf{jointly}
\begin{itemize}
\item Costs and benefit will tend to be correlated
\begin{itemize}
\item Strong positive correlation --- effective treatments are innovative and result from intensive and lengthy research $\Rightarrow$ are associated with higher unit costs
\item Negative correlation --- more effective treatments may reduce total care pathway costs e.g.\ by reducing hospitalisations, side effects, etc.
\end{itemize}
\item In any case, the economic evaluation is based on both!
\end{itemize}
\vspace{5pt}\pause
\item There are different ways in which we can define $\myblue (e,c)$ for a specific problem
\begin{itemize}
\item Direct vs indirect vs intangible costs
\item ``Hard-'' vs utility-based clinical outcomes 
\item Public (\eg NHS) vs private (\eg insurance) perspective
\end{itemize}
\end{itemize}
}

\frame{
\frametitle{Cost distributions}
\vspace{-6pt}
\begin{itemize}
\item Cost variables usually have the following characteristics
\begin{itemize}
\item Can vary widely between patients
\item Are bounded by 0 and potentially have no upper limit 
\item Sometimes, ``structural'' 0 are observed (ie patients that induce no costs)
\item Simple statistical models fail to provide a reasonable fit to the observed data (\textbf{more on this later!})
%%%\item Hence tend to be positively skewed 
\end{itemize} 
\end{itemize}
\vspace{-6pt}
\begin{center}
\begin{tabular}{cc}
\includegraphics[scale=.35]{1.introduction-to-health-economic-evaluations/figs/costCtrl} & 
\includegraphics[scale=.35]{1.introduction-to-health-economic-evaluations/figs/costTrts}
\end{tabular}
\end{center}
}

%%%%\frame{
%%%%\frametitle{Clinical outcomes}
%%%%\begin{itemize}
%%%%\item For some specific analysis, we can use ``hard'' clinical measures of outcome
%%%%\begin{itemize}
%%%%\item Cases of tuberculosis (TB) prevented for a TB screening programme
%%%%\item Days of normal functioning gained for patients with schizophrenia that have received cognitive behavioural therapy
%%%%\item Life years saved as part of a colorectal cancer screening programme
%%%%\item Number of deaths averted by a surgical procedure
%%%%\end{itemize}
%%%%\item However, unless the same outcome is used (eg life years saved), it is difficult to compare interventions across disease areas 
%%%%\end{itemize}
%%%%\vspace{10pt}\pause
%%%%
%%%%\begin{itemize}
%%%%\item For this reason, we often use suitable generic instruments for measuring health outcomes
%%%%\begin{itemize}
%%%%\item Because they have a standardised description of health, they allow for a comparison of outcomes across different disease areas
%%%%\end{itemize}
%%%%\item Examples of general health profile instruments include
%%%%\begin{itemize}
%%%%\item The \textit{Short Form 36} (SF-36)
%%%%\item The \textit{Nottingham Health Profile}
%%%%\end{itemize}
%%%%\end{itemize}
%%%%}
%%%%
