\frame{
\frametitle{1.\ Statistical modelling}
\begin{itemize}
\item \red Sampling variability \black for the health economic outcomes is described by a distribution $\myblue p(e,c\mid \bm\theta^t)$, which depends on a set of population parameters~$\bm\theta^t$
\begin{itemize}
\item Probability of some clinical outcome
\item Duration in treatment
\item Reduction in the rate of occurrence of some event
\item Unit cost of acquisition of a health technology
\end{itemize}
\vspace{5pt}\pause
\item Under the Bayesian approach, \red parametric uncertainty \black is modelled using a prior distribution $\myblue p(\bm\theta^t)$
\begin{itemize}
\item This describes the level of knowledge in the value of the population parameters
\item Can be based on subjective information, or existing data 
\end{itemize}

\vspace{5pt}\pause
\item The way in which we construct our statistical model, depends on 
\begin{itemize}
\item The characteristic of the available data (\textbf{\color{blue}individual-level} vs \textbf{\color{red}aggregated} data)
\item The statistical framework (Bayesian vs frequentist)
\end{itemize}
\end{itemize}
}

\frame{
\frametitle{RCT vs decision-analytical models}
\textbf{(Individual vs aggregated data)}
\begin{itemize}
\item RCTs are a key component in the evaluation of health care interventions
\begin{itemize}
\item Usually individual-level data are collected for a clinical study and increasingly often complemented by financial outcomes
\end{itemize}
\item However, there may issues with RCTs data
\begin{itemize}
\item Comparator(s) in the trial may not reflect standard of care
\item Limited follow up 
\item Small sample size
\item Poor external validity
\end{itemize}
\item Health economic evaluations should include information from as many sources as possible
\begin{itemize}
\item Evidence synthesis of literature 
\item Network meta-analysis
\end{itemize}
\end{itemize}
}

