%%%\frame{
%%%\frametitle{Decision-analytic models}
%%%\vspace{0pt}
%%%\begin{itemize}
%%%\item Often, we do not have access to individual data and all we have is a set of aggregated data on relevant quantities
%%%\item These can in turn be used to construct a ``population model'' to describe the disease history and its implications
%%%\begin{itemize}
%%%\item Decision trees
%%%\item Markov (multistate) models
%%%\end{itemize}
%%%\end{itemize}
%%%
%%%\vspace{5pt}\pause
%%%\textbf{Example}: influenza (\textbf{more on this later!})
%%%\vspace{-8pt}
%%%\begin{center}
%%%\includegraphics[scale=.9]{1.introduction-to-health-economic-evaluations/figs/Decision_model}
%%%\end{center}
%%%}

\frame{
\frametitle{2.\ Economic modelling (types of evaluations)}
\begin{itemize}
\item Cost minimisation 
\begin{itemize}
\item Assumes that the benefits produced by two interventions are identical $\Rightarrow$ the only dimension of interest is costs
\end{itemize}
\item Cost-benefit analysis
\begin{itemize}
\item Requires that costs and benefits are converted and analysed into monetary terms $\Rightarrow$ difficulties in valuing health outcomes in monetary units
\end{itemize}
\vspace{5pt}\pause
\item \textbf{\color{red}Cost-effectiveness analysis} (CEA)
\begin{itemize}
\item Evaluates \alert{cost-per-outcome gained}
\item Outcomes are usually ``hard'' measurements (eg death) $\Rightarrow$ easy to understand for clinicians, but difficult to compare across diseases (may have different main outcome)
\end{itemize}
\item \textbf{\color{blue}Cost-utility analysis} (CUA)
\begin{itemize}
\item Considers a common health outcome unit (= QALYs), so easy to compare across diseases
\item Often interchangeable with CEA (common methodology!)
\end{itemize}
\end{itemize}
}

\frame{
\frametitle{2.\ Economic modelling}
Can think of this step as the process of obtaining relevant population summaries for the measures of cost \& clinical benefits. For example, when comparing two interventions $t=0,1$, the main focus is on
\begin{itemize}
\item The \textbf{\blue increment in mean benefits}
\[\myblue \Delta_e=\red\underbrace{\myblue\mbox{E}[e \mid \theta^1]}_{\mu_1^e} \myblue - \red\underbrace{\myblue\mbox{E}[e \mid \theta^0]}_{\mu_0^e}\]\vspace{-10pt}
\item The \textbf{\blue increment in mean costs}:
\[ \myblue \Delta_c=\red\underbrace{\myblue\mbox{E}[c \mid \theta^1]}_{\mu_1^c} \myblue - \red\underbrace{\myblue\mbox{E}[c \mid \theta^0]}_{\mu_0^c} \]\vspace{-10pt}\pause
\item \textbf{NB}: In a Bayesian context, these are functions of $\boldsymbol\theta$ and thus random variables!
\item When using individual-level data, estimation typically directly available from the statistical model; for aggregated data, it may be necessary to combine the parameters to obtain these
\end{itemize}
}

\frame{
\frametitle{Cost effectiveness plane}
\begin{figure}
\begin{tikzpicture}
\node{\includegraphics[scale=.55]{1.introduction-to-health-economic-evaluations/figs/CEPlane_empty}};
\draw(3.5,-.1) node[align=center,rectangle,rounded corners,draw=none,text width=4.1cm](8){\fontsize{8}{8}\selectfont $\Delta_e$};
\draw(-.9,3.2) node[align=center,rectangle,rounded corners,draw=none,text width=4.1cm](8){\fontsize{8}{8}\selectfont $\Delta_c$};
\end{tikzpicture}
\end{figure}
}

\frame{
\frametitle{3.\ Decision analysis}
\vspace{10pt}
In order to compare the two interventions ($t=0,1$), we define suitable health economic indicators
\begin{itemize}
\item The \textbf{\color{red} population average increment in benefits}
\[ \color{myblue} \mbox{E}[\Delta_e]=\bar{e}_1 - \bar{e}_0  = \mbox{E}[\mu_1^e]-\mbox{E}[\mu_0^e]\]\vspace{-10pt}
\item The \textbf{\color{red} population average increment in costs}:
\[ \color{myblue} \mbox{E}[\Delta_c]=\bar{c}_1 - \bar{c}_0 = \mbox{E}[\mu_1^c]-\mbox{E}[\mu_0^c] \]\vspace{-10pt}
\pause
\item Generally, economic summaries are computed in the form of ``cost per outcome'' ratios
\[ \color{myblue} \mbox{ICER} = \frac{\mbox{E}[\Delta_c]}{\mbox{E}[\Delta_e]} = \mbox{\color{blue} Additional cost to gain 1 unit of benefit} \]
\end{itemize}
}

\frame{
\frametitle{Cost effectiveness plane vs.\ ICER}
\begin{figure}
\begin{tikzpicture}
\node{\includegraphics[scale=.55]{1.introduction-to-health-economic-evaluations/figs/CEPlane_ICER}};
\draw(3.5,-.1) node[align=center,rectangle,rounded corners,draw=none,text width=4.1cm](8){\fontsize{8}{8}\selectfont $\Delta_e$};
\draw(-.9,3.2) node[align=center,rectangle,rounded corners,draw=none,text width=4.1cm](8){\fontsize{8}{8}\selectfont $\Delta_c$};
\draw(2.5,1.6) node[align=center,rectangle,rounded corners,draw=none,text width=6.0cm](8){\fontsize{8}{8}\selectfont $\mbox{ICER}=\frac{\mbox{E$[\Delta_c]$}}{\mbox{E$[\Delta_e]$}}=\mbox{Cost per QALY}$};
\end{tikzpicture}
\end{figure}
}

\frame{
\frametitle{Comparing health interventions}
Decisions based on ICER can be tricky
\begin{itemize}
\item Equivalent ICERs can mean very different things!
\begin{itemize}
\item $\color{blue}(\mbox{E}[\Delta_e],\mbox{E}[\Delta_c])=(2,200)$, indicates that the new treatment produces on average an increase in effectiveness of 2 units at the cost of extra \pounds 200
\item $\color{red}(\mbox{E}[\Delta_e],\mbox{E}[\Delta_c])=(-2,-200)$ indicates that the new intervention is less effective, but cheaper
\item In both cases, ICER = \pounds 100
\end{itemize}
\vspace{5pt}
%\item The ratio $\color{myblue} \Delta_c/\Delta_e$ can have infinite variance and it is generally difficult to perform interval estimation for its values
\item \textbf{NB}: the ICER is a \alert{``pure'' number (dimension-less)}
\begin{itemize}
\item It is a ratio of two expected values --- all forms of uncertainty are marginalised out when computing it
\item Not meaningful to make interval estimation 
\item \textbf{More on this later!}
\end{itemize}
\end{itemize}
\vspace{15pt}
Thus, it is helpful to re-phrase the problem in decision theoretic terms (\textbf{more on this later!})
}

